tegration":0.7,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A write to the underlying PostgreSQL table invalidates all cache entries whose keys match the affected rows.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is the critical integration boundary between cache and database. The real failure — 'cache returns stale data after DB update' — cannot be caught by mocking the write or mocking invalidation alone. The test must verify: (1) write reaches database, (2) system detects the write and computes affected cache keys, (3) those entries are actually invalidated. This requires a real (test) PostgreSQL database and live cache wired together. System-level testing is needed only if invalidation uses PostgreSQL WAL or triggers; standard app-level write interception is testable at Integration.","test_description":"Set up a test PostgreSQL database with sample rows. Populate the cache with entries derived from those rows. Perform a write operation (UPDATE one row, DELETE multiple rows, INSERT new row). Verify that cache entries matching the affected rows' keys are invalidated. Verify unrelated cache entries remain valid. Test: single-row updates, multi-row deletes, concurrent writes and cache reads, invalidation timing (does stale read ever occur between write and invalidation?), and correctness of key-to-affected-rows computation.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The eviction policy removes the correct entries — least-recently-used under LRU, least-frequently-used under LFU — when the cache is full.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is pure algorithm verification. Given a cache state (entry timestamps and frequency counts) and a full cache, the eviction logic must correctly identify and remove the target entry. A real failure (evicts most-recently-used instead of least, miscounts frequency, corrupts other entries) can be caught entirely in-process without I/O, databases, or external services. The logic is self-contained, deterministic, and has no external dependencies to mock.","test_description":"For LRU: create a cache with a known access sequence (e.g., access A, B, C, A, B). Fill to capacity. Trigger eviction and verify C (least-recently-used) is removed and remaining entries are intact. For LFU: populate with entries having different frequencies (A: 10 accesses, B: 5, C: 1). Trigger eviction and verify C is removed. Test: tie-breaking rules when multiple entries have same recency/frequency, eviction correctness under different cache sizes, and that non-evicted entries remain valid with correct state (no timestamp/frequency corruption).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.88,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13570,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13570},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9afa9b7e-7ac8-44f9-aa16-4fdb36092f6c","uuid":"4365525a-afe1-4152-979d-c1e76a24f576"}
